function maxScore(nums1, nums2, k) {
    const n = nums1.length;
    let res = 0;
    let sum_n1 = 0, min_n2 = nums2[0];
    for (let i = 0, j = 0; j < n; j++) {
        sum_n1 += nums1[j];
        min_n2 = Math.min(min_n2, nums2[j]);
        if (j - i + 1 > k) sum_n1 -= nums1[i++];
        if (j + 1 >= k) res = Math.max(res, sum_n1 * min_n2);
    }
    return res;
}
```


    For this problem, we can use the sliding window technique. Keeping two pointers `i` and `j`, we can iterate through the two input arrays `nums1` and `nums2` simultaneously. The length of the current subsequence is `j - i + 1`. If the length of the subsequence is greater than `k`, remove `nums1[i]` from the sum, and increment `i`. Calculate the minimum `nums2` value within the window during the process. For any subsequence of length `k`, compare the current score with the previous max score, and update the result if needed. At the end, return the maximum score.

